          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>In the case where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is compact, a generalisation of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.1.2" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.1.2.xml" taxon="Corollary" number="4.1.2" /> is proven by analytic methods in [<fr:link type="local" href="G1970.xml" addr="G1970" title="Periods of integrals on algebraic manifolds, III">G1970</fr:link>].</fr:p>
            <fr:p>As a corollary to <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.1.2" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.1.2.xml" taxon="Corollary" number="4.1.2" />, we note:

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>386</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-4.1.3.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-4.1.3.1.xml</fr:route><fr:authors /><fr:number>4.1.3.1</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>(cf. [<fr:link type="local" href="G1970.xml" addr="G1970" title="Periods of integrals on algebraic manifolds, III">G1970</fr:link>]).
        Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  X\to  S]]></fr:tex> be a proper smooth morphism, as in <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.1.2" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.1.2.xml" taxon="Corollary" number="4.1.2" />.
        If a global section <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R}^n f_*\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> is of Hodge degree <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(p,q)]]></fr:tex> at a point, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> is everywhere of degree <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(p,q)]]></fr:tex>.
        In particular, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n=2]]></fr:tex> and if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> is, at some point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s]]></fr:tex>, the cohomology class of a divisor of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_s]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> is everywhere the cohomology class of a divisor, and, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is smooth, is even defined by a divisor <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>387</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-4.1.3.2</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-4.1.3.2.xml</fr:route><fr:authors /><fr:number>4.1.3.2</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>(cf. [<fr:link type="local" href="G1966.xml" addr="G1966" title="Un théorème sur les homomorphismes de schémas abéliens">G1966</fr:link>]).
        Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> be a reduced connected scheme of finite type over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>, and let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f_1\colon  X_1\to  S]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f_2\colon  X_2\to  S]]></fr:tex> be abelian schemes over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.
        If a morphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u\colon \mathrm {R}^1{f_2}_*\mathbb {Z}\to \mathrm {R}^1{f_1}_*\mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex> comes from a morphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\widetilde {u}_s\colon (X_1)_s\to (X_2)_s]]></fr:tex> of abelian varieties at some point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s\in  S]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex> comes from a (unique) morphism of abelian schemes <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\widetilde {u}\colon  X_1\to  X_2]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>388</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-4.1.3.3</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-4.1.3.3.xml</fr:route><fr:authors /><fr:number>4.1.3.3</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>(cf. [<fr:link type="local" href="K1971.xml" addr="K1971" title="Nilpotent connections and the monodromy theorem. Applications of a result of Turritin">K1971</fr:link>]).
        Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> be a smooth connected scheme, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s\in  S]]></fr:tex> a point, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  X\to  S]]></fr:tex> a proper smooth morphism, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> a direct factor of the local system <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R}^i f_*\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex>, which is pointwise a Hodge sub-structure.
        Then the following conditions are equivalent:

        
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
          
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(a) &quot;">
            The Hodge structure of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> is locally constant.
          </html:li>

          
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(b) &quot;">
            The representation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P_s]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\pi _1(S,s)]]></fr:tex> factors through a finite quotient of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\pi _1(S,s)]]></fr:tex>.
          </html:li>

          
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(c) &quot;">
            There exists a finite non-empty étale covering <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u\colon  S'\to  S]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u^*P]]></fr:tex> is a constant family of Hodge structures.
          </html:li>

        </html:ol></fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:p>
