        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>1703</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-4.4.11</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-4.4.11.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:number>4.4.11</fr:number>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> be a non-empty, connected, smooth scheme, with generic point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\eta ]]></fr:tex>, and let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  X\to  S]]></fr:tex> be an abelian scheme over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.
    Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H=\operatorname {End}(\mathbb {R}_1f_*\mathbb {Q})]]></fr:tex>, and let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Z]]></fr:tex> be the centre of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex>.
    Suppose that

    
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(a) &quot;">
        <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\eta ]]></fr:tex> is simple over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k(\eta )]]></fr:tex>.
      </html:li>


      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(b) &quot;">
        <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> does not become constant on any finite covering of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.
      </html:li>


      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(c) &quot;">
        One of the following conditions is satisfied (cf. <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.5" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.5.xml" taxon="Reminder" number="4.4.5" />):

        
 <html:ol>
          
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(1) &quot;">
            <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Z]]></fr:tex> is imaginary <fr:em>quadratic</fr:em>;
          </html:li>

          
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(2) &quot;">
            <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Z]]></fr:tex> is completely real, and for each real embedding <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\varphi \colon  Z\to \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H\otimes _{Z,\varphi }\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> is an algebra of matrices over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>;
          </html:li>

          
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(3) &quot;">
            <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Z]]></fr:tex> is completely real, and for each real embedding <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\varphi \colon  Z\to \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H\otimes _{Z,\varphi }\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> is an algebra of matrices over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {H}]]></fr:tex>.
          </html:li>

        </html:ol>

      </html:li>

    </html:ol></fr:p><fr:p>Then
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       \operatorname {End}(X)       \xrightarrow {\sim } \operatorname {End}(\mathrm {R}_1f_*\mathbb {Z}).     ]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1686</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">#281</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-281.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:authors /></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>We will show that we are either in case (a) or case (b) of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.8" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.8.xml" number="4.4.8" />, for every place of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Z]]></fr:tex> simultaneously.
      This is clear (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.8" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.8.xml" number="4.4.8" />) under the hypothesis (c.1), and follows from <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.10" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.10.xml" taxon="Lemma" number="4.4.10" /> under the hypotheses (c.2) or (c.3), since not only <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\varepsilon _T]]></fr:tex>, but also <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\varepsilon _{H\rho }]]></fr:tex>, is then independent of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\rho ]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>

    <fr:p>Condition (b) of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.8" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.8.xml" number="4.4.8" /> cannot be satisfied at every place of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Z]]></fr:tex>, since the Hodge structure would then be locally constant, which (by <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.1.3.3" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.1.3.3.xml" number="4.1.3.3" /> and <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.3" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.3.xml" taxon="Reminder" number="4.4.3" />) contradicts (b).
      Condition (a) is thus satisfied at each place of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Z]]></fr:tex>, and so <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> is of degree <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(0,0)]]></fr:tex> (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.8" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.8.xml" number="4.4.8" />).
      Taking <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.3" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.3.xml" taxon="Reminder" number="4.4.3" /> into account, this finishes the proof.</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
  
</fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>1704</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-4.4.13</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-4.4.13.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:taxon>Corollary</fr:taxon>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:number>4.4.13</fr:number>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> be a smooth connected scheme with generic point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\eta ]]></fr:tex>, and let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  X\to  S]]></fr:tex> be an abelian scheme over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> of relative dimension <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g\leqslant 3]]></fr:tex>.
    Suppose that, on any finite étale covering of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> does not admit a constant abelian subscheme.
    Then, for every abelian scheme <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g\colon  Y\to  S]]></fr:tex>, we have
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       \begin {aligned}         \operatorname {Hom}(X,Y)         &\xrightarrow {\sim } \operatorname {Hom}(\mathrm {R}_1f_*\mathbb {Z},\mathrm {R}_1g_*\mathbb {Z})       \\\operatorname {Hom}(Y,X)         &\xrightarrow {\sim } \operatorname {Hom}(\mathrm {R}_1g_*\mathbb {Z},\mathrm {R}_1f_*\mathbb {Z}).       \end {aligned}     ]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1689</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">#283</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-283.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:authors /></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>By duality, it suffices to prove the first claim.
      We can also suppose <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\eta ]]></fr:tex> to be simple.
      We will show that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> satisfies one of the conditions of (c) in <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.11" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.11.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="4.4.11" />.</fr:p>

    <fr:p>Set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H=\mathbb {M}_c(D)]]></fr:tex>, with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex> a skew field of rank <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b^2]]></fr:tex> over its centre <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Z]]></fr:tex>, which we know to be either completely real or completely imaginary.
      If we set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a=[Z:\mathbb {Q}]]]></fr:tex>, then we have

      <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1690</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-4.4.13.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-4.4.13.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>4.4.13.1</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[           ab^2c \mathbin {\vert } 2g \leqslant  6.         \tag{4.4.13.1}         ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:p>

    
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(i) &quot;">
        <fr:p>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Z]]></fr:tex> is completely imaginary, and not imaginary quadratic, then we must have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a=2g=4]]></fr:tex>.
          For <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s\in  S]]></fr:tex>, the centraliser of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Z]]></fr:tex> acting on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(\mathrm {R}_1f_*\mathbb {Q})_s]]></fr:tex> is thus commutative, and so the action of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\pi _1(S,s)]]></fr:tex> is abelian, and thus factors through a finite group ((iii.b) of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.2.8" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.2.8.xml" taxon="Corollary" number="4.2.8" /> or <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.2.9" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.2.9.xml" taxon="Corollary" number="4.2.9" />).
          This is a contradiction (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.1.3.3" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.1.3.3.xml" number="4.1.3.3" /> and <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.3" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.3.xml" taxon="Reminder" number="4.4.3" />).</fr:p>

        <fr:p>With the notation of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.8" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.8.xml" number="4.4.8" />, we can also note that the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[T_\rho ]]></fr:tex> are then of rank <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1]]></fr:tex>, and so condition (b) of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.8" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.8.xml" number="4.4.8" /> is satisfied at each place, and the Hodge structure is locally constant.</fr:p>
      </html:li>


      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(ii) &quot;">
        If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Z]]></fr:tex> is completely real, and if conditions (c.1) and (c.2) are not satisfied, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\geqslant 2]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b\geqslant 2]]></fr:tex>, which is a contradiction.
      </html:li>

    </html:ol>


    <fr:p>We will show that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> satisfies the conditions of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.12" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.12.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="4.4.12" />.
      If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Z]]></fr:tex> is imaginary quadratic, and if there exists <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\rho \colon  Z\to \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R}_1f_*\mathbb {Q}\otimes _{Z,\rho }\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> is of pure Hodge type <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(-1,0)]]></fr:tex>, then the Hodge structure on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R}_1f_*\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex> is locally constant, which is a contradiction.
      This proves <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.13" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.13.xml" taxon="Corollary" number="4.4.13" />.</fr:p>
